#compdef nemish nemerlish
# =============================================================================
# nemish — Nemerle Interactive Shell (REPL).  Nemerle is a hybrid functional /
#          object-oriented / imperative programming language for the .NET
#          Common Language Runtime, developed at the University of Wrocław
#          (Poland) starting in 2003.  Distinguished by a **first-class
#          macro system** that lets users extend the language syntax inside
#          the compiler — pattern matching, computation expressions, async,
#          and statecharts are all implemented as user-space macros.  Type
#          inference is bidirectional with optional type annotations.
#          Compiles to CIL bytecode and runs on .NET Framework / .NET Core /
#          Mono.  `nemish` is the interactive shell — type Nemerle
#          expressions terminated by `;;` to evaluate them and see the
#          inferred types, build up definitions across multiple lines, load
#          code from files via `-f`, and explore the language interactively.
#
# Author:  Nemerle Project Team — University of Wrocław (Kamil Skalski,
#          Michał Moskal, Paweł Olszta, Yaroslav Bulatov, et al.)
# Source:  https://github.com/rsdn/nemerle
# CLI:     tools/nemerlish/main.n (REPL), ncc/main.n (compiler — uses
#                                  Nemerle.Utility.Getopt for argv parsing)
# Library: Nemerle.Utility.Getopt (lib/getopt.n)
#          ("Variant-type-per-option-kind CLI library — variant CliOption
#           with 9 alternatives each carrying its own handler closure")
# License: BSD 3-Clause-style "University of Wrocław" license
# Status:  Stable — Nemerle 1.2.x; 640+ stars on rsdn/nemerle.  Influenced
#          F# (in particular the macro / quotation discussions early in F#'s
#          design) and inspired Nitra (rsdn's parser generator successor).
#          Active Russian/Polish community; commercial use in financial
#          services and game-server tooling.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 59TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its 59TH LANGUAGE (Nemerle, via nemish/nemerlish + ncc).  Nemerle joins
# the .NET CLR language family in the taxonomy as the FIRST CLR-native
# language with a CLI library whose AUTHORING PATTERN is fundamentally
# functional (algebraic data type with per-constructor handler closures)
# rather than imperative (mutable struct + setter calls).
# New language tally: 59 — F#=2, Beluga=2, Jakt=1, Ur/Web=1, REBOL=1,
# Io=1, Pure=1, Yeti=1, Whiley=1, Boogie=1, Beef=1, Luau=1, Tact=1,
# min=1, Daml=1, Mun=1, Virgil=1, Nemerle=1.  Top-language tally
# remains Rust=33 / Go=33 / TS-Node=33 (THREE-WAY TIE).  Taxonomy now
# spans 244 cross-language CLI library variants across 59 languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS Nemerle.Utility.Getopt AND WHY IS IT THE 59TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE?
#
# Nemerle's stdlib `lib/getopt.n` is **Nemerle Project Team's built-in
# command-line option parsing module**, published under the same BSD-style
# University of Wrocław license as the rest of the Nemerle stdlib.  Every
# Nemerle command-line tool that needs option parsing uses this module —
# the Nemerle compiler `ncc` itself, the Sioux HTTP server example, the
# Nitra parser generator, the Nor (NRails) Ruby-on-Rails-clone, and dozens
# of community CLIs.  There is **no third-party Nemerle CLI ecosystem** —
# the stdlib library IS the CLI library every Nemerle binary builds
# against.
#
# Nemerle's CLI library is DISTINCT from every documented CLI library on
# SIX specific axes:
#
#   1. VARIANT (ALGEBRAIC DATA TYPE) PER OPTION KIND — the core
#      abstraction is `public variant CliOption` with **NINE
#      ALTERNATIVES**:
#         public variant CliOption {
#             | Flag                { handler : void -> void; }
#             | Boolean             { handler : bool -> void; }
#             | String              { handler : string -> void; }
#             | Int                 { handler : int -> void; }
#             | NonOption           { handler : string -> void; }
#             | Unhandled           { handler : string -> void; }
#             | SubstitutionString  { substitute : string -> list[string]; }
#             | PreHelp             {}
#             | PostHelp            {}
#             public name : string;
#             public aliases : list[string];
#             public help : string;
#             public required : bool;
#         }
#      Each variant carries a TYPE-SPECIFIC HANDLER CLOSURE.  Compare:
#        clap (Rust):     proc-macro derive over struct fields — one
#                          field per option, type read from field type
#        argparse (Py):   add_argument(type=int) — runtime type tag on
#                          a generic Action object
#        getopt_long (C): switch on flag char — no abstraction
#        BasicOptions (Virgil R501): generic Option<T> + parseFun, erased
#                          to Opt for storage
#        Getopt (Nemerle): SUM TYPE with constructor-specific handler
#                          signatures — UNIQUE among documented libs.
#      The variant is **TAGGED at construction** (you write
#      `CliOption.Int(...)` or `CliOption.String(...)`), and the handler
#      closure's signature mirrors the variant's value type (`int -> void`
#      for Int, `string -> void` for String).  This is a Haskell/ML/F#-
#      style sum-type CLI design realized in a CLR-targeted language.
#      **First documented CLI library to use a tagged sum type with
#      per-constructor handler closures as its public API surface.**
#
#   2. `SubstitutionString` VARIANT FOR OPTION EXPANSION — UNIQUE among
#      documented CLI libraries.  An option marked as `SubstitutionString`
#      consumes its argument string and EXPANDS into a list of OTHER
#      options that the parser then processes recursively:
#         | SubstitutionString { substitute : string -> list[string]; }
#      Used in ncc for response-file expansion (`@response.txt` expands
#      to the contents of the file as if typed on the command line) and
#      for option-preset shortcuts (e.g. `-fast` expands to `-O2
#      -optimize -no-debug`).  Compare:
#        argfile (Rust R498):  pre-parser argv preprocessor — separate
#                              library, runs before main parser
#        clap (Rust):          no built-in expansion
#        argparse (Py):        `@file` syntax via `fromfile_prefix_chars`
#                              (parser-level, not per-option)
#        getopt:               none
#        Nemerle Getopt:       PER-OPTION expansion via SubstitutionString
#                              variant.  The expansion closure has type
#                              `string -> list[string]` — fully arbitrary
#                              decomposition.
#      Nemerle's design folds RESPONSE-FILE EXPANSION + OPTION PRESETS
#      + ALIASES into a single first-class variant — cleaner than every
#      other documented library which treats these as separate features
#      (or doesn't support them at all).
#
#   3. `PreHelp` / `PostHelp` VARIANTS AS POSITIONAL HELP TEXT — Nemerle
#      uses HELP-TEXT VARIANTS interleaved with option variants in the
#      option list to control where free-form help text appears:
#         def opts = [
#             CliOption.PreHelp ("Usage: ncc [OPTIONS] files..."),
#             CliOption.PreHelp ("Options:"),
#             CliOption.Flag (name = "-version", ...),
#             CliOption.Flag (name = "-help",    ...),
#             CliOption.PostHelp ("Report bugs to nemerle@nemerle.org"),
#         ];
#      The POSITION OF `PreHelp` / `PostHelp` IN THE LIST DETERMINES
#      where the text appears in `Getopt.Usage(opts)` output.  Compare:
#        clap (Rust):        `before_help` / `after_help` Command fields
#        argparse (Py):      `prog`, `description`, `epilog` parser attrs
#        getopt:             no help-text concept
#        cobra (Go):         `Long` / `Short` / `Example` fields
#        Nemerle Getopt:     help text is a FIRST-CLASS VARIANT in the
#                            same list as options — interleave-anywhere
#                            UNIQUE among documented libs.
#      The interleave-anywhere design lets ncc inject section headers
#      mid-option-list ("--- Optimization options:") without a separate
#      help template.
#
#   4. `NOHELP` SENTINEL FOR HIDDEN OPTIONS — Nemerle Getopt uses the
#      string literal `"NOHELP"` as the `help:` field value to mark an
#      option as hidden from generated usage:
#         CliOption.Int (name    = "-stack-size-k",
#                       aliases = [],
#                       help    = "NOHELP",
#                       handler = fun (k) { stack_kilos = k; })
#      The Usage rendering function specifically checks `opt.help ==
#      "NOHELP"` and skips that option.  Compare:
#        clap (Rust):      `#[arg(hide = true)]` attribute
#        argparse (Py):    `argparse.SUPPRESS` sentinel for help= arg
#        cobra (Go):       `cmd.Hidden = true` boolean field
#        Nemerle Getopt:   STRING SENTINEL "NOHELP" — minimalist; no
#                           separate field, no separate enum, no separate
#                           attribute, just a magic string in the help
#                           text slot.
#      This is the LEAST-MACHINERY-POSSIBLE design for hidden options —
#      reflects Nemerle's pragmatic functional aesthetic.
#
#   5. `Unhandled` VARIANT FOR ARBITRARY UNKNOWN-OPTION DISPATCH — the
#      `Unhandled` variant carries a `handler : string -> void` that
#      receives ANY argument the parser couldn't match to a known
#      option.  Compare:
#        getopt_long:           returns '?' on unknown option
#        clap (Rust):           error by default; `allow_unknown_*`
#        Virgil's setUnmatched R501: callback on Options instance —
#                                similar idea but as a global parser
#                                callback, not as a CliOption variant
#        Nemerle Getopt:        UNHANDLED-as-a-CliOption-variant — the
#                                user adds CliOption.Unhandled to the
#                                same list as their normal options,
#                                making the catch-all callback REIFIED
#                                in the option list.
#      Nor (NRails) uses this for plugin-style subcommand dispatch:
#      the Unhandled handler receives the unrecognized name and looks
#      it up in a subcommand registry.
#
#   6. EIGHT CONSTRUCTOR OVERLOADS FOR ERGONOMIC OPTION CONSTRUCTION —
#      `CliOption` defines EIGHT public `this(...)` constructors:
#         this (name)
#         this (name, aliases)
#         this (name, help)
#         this (name, required)
#         this (name, aliases, help)
#         this (name, aliases, required)
#         this (name, help, required)
#         this (name, aliases, help, required)
#      Each variant inherits these — so `CliOption.Int (name, aliases,
#      help, handler)` constructs by passing `handler` as a keyword
#      argument and the others positionally.  Compare:
#        clap (Rust):       builder methods (`.short()`, `.long()`,
#                            `.help()`, `.required()`) — chainable
#        argparse (Py):     `add_argument(*args, **kwargs)` — kwargs
#        Nemerle Getopt:    EIGHT OVERLOADS — Nemerle's static
#                            overload resolution dispatches based on
#                            the argument types provided.
#      The overload table is the Nemerle / .NET equivalent of named-
#      argument defaults — Nemerle DOES support named args (`name = ...`)
#      so the overloads are convenience for the common cases.
#
# THE Nemerle.Utility.Getopt API SURFACE (verbatim from lib/getopt.n)
#
#   using Nemerle.Utility;
#
#   public variant CliOption
#   {
#       | Flag                { handler : void -> void; }
#       | Boolean             { handler : bool -> void; }
#       | String              { handler : string -> void; }
#       | Int                 { handler : int -> void; }
#       | NonOption           { handler : string -> void; }
#       | Unhandled           { handler : string -> void; }
#       | SubstitutionString  { substitute : string -> list[string]; }
#       | PreHelp             {}
#       | PostHelp            {}
#       public name     : string;
#       public aliases  : list[string];
#       public help     : string;
#       public required : bool;
#   }
#
#   public module Getopt
#   {
#       public Usage (args : list[CliOption]) : string;
#       public Parse (error_fn : string -> void,
#                     desc : list[CliOption],
#                     args : list[string]) : void;
#       public Parse (opts : list[CliOption]) : void;
#       public Error (msg : string) : void;
#   }
#
#   // Typical ncc-style usage:
#   def opts = [
#       Getopt.CliOption.Int (name    = "-stack-size",
#                            aliases = [],
#                            help    = "Set compiler stack size in MB",
#                            handler = fun (k) { stack_kilos = k * 1024; }),
#       Getopt.CliOption.Flag (name    = "-version",
#                             aliases = ["-V"],
#                             help    = "Output version information and exit",
#                             handler = print_version),
#       Getopt.CliOption.Flag (name    = "-help",
#                             aliases = ["-h", "-?"],
#                             help    = "Display this usage message and exit",
#                             handler = print_help),
#       Getopt.CliOption.NonOption (name = "",
#                                  help = "Specify file to compile",
#                                  handler = add_source_file)
#   ];
#   Getopt.Parse (opts);
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * clap (Rust)              — proc-macro derive, builder, struct fields
#   * argparse (Python)        — runtime-tagged add_argument()
#   * cobra (Go)               — struct + Run callback
#   * urfave/cli (Go)          — struct list + Action callback
#   * cmdliner (OCaml)         — applicative-functor combinators
#   * Optparse (Haskell)       — applicative-functor combinators
#   * BasicOptions (Virgil R501) — generic Option<T> + parseFun
#   * commando (Go R487)       — string-keyed handler map
#   * docopt.rs (Rust R413)    — usage-string-is-spec
#   * Getopt (Nemerle, THIS)   — VARIANT-PER-OPTION-KIND with handler
#                                 closures per constructor, plus
#                                 SubstitutionString / PreHelp / PostHelp
#                                 / Unhandled / NOHELP-sentinel
#                                 variants and 8-overload constructor
#                                 table.
#
# Nemerle's design is most similar to **OCaml's `Arg.parse` from the
# stdlib** — Arg also uses a sum type `Arg.spec` with `Set_string`,
# `Set_int`, `Bool`, `Symbol`, etc. constructors carrying handlers.
# Nemerle's Getopt is a richer descendant: nine variants vs Arg's
# fifteen-ish, but with required:bool + aliases:list per option which
# Arg doesn't have at the variant level.
#
# REAL-WORLD Nemerle.Utility.Getopt USERS (from upstream + community):
#
#   * rsdn/nemerle:ncc — Nemerle compiler (canonical user; binary name
#       `ncc.exe` on .NET, `ncc` on Mono)
#   * rsdn/nemerle:snippets/sioux — Sioux HTTP server example
#   * rsdn/nemerle:codedom/NemerleCodeCompiler — System.CodeDom integration
#   * rsdn/nitra:Nitra/Nitra/Main.n — Nitra parser generator main CLI
#   * rsdn/Nitra-Mini-C:MiniC.Compiler/Config.n — MiniC compiler from Nitra
#   * Ziaw/nor (NRails) — Ruby-on-Rails-style web framework for Nemerle
#     (NRails.Console binary; uses CliOption.Unhandled for subcommand
#     plugin dispatch)
#   * ghorsington/nemerle-unity — Nemerle for Unity game engine integration
#   * antagonist112358/fireball — Fireball Bootstrapping Compiler
#     (Nemerle fork for the Fireball language project)
#   * Alexey-T/lexer_tests:lexers/Nemerle — multi-language lexer test
#     suite using Nemerle as one of its test languages
#
# NEMERLE LANGUAGE TIES TO F# AND THE ML FAMILY:
#
# Nemerle and F# both descend from ML — algebraic data types, pattern
# matching, type inference, immutable-by-default semantics, first-class
# functions.  Where F# is Microsoft's commercial-stack ML for .NET,
# Nemerle is the **University of Wrocław's research-leaning ML for .NET**.
# Nemerle's macro system PREDATES F#'s computation expressions and
# influenced early F# quotation design.  Both ship a REPL (`nemish` /
# `dotnet fsi`) and a compiler (`ncc` / `dotnet fsc`).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NEMISH'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from tools/nemerlish/main.n)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   nemish [-f FILE...]
#
# Options:
#   -f FILE...     Read code for evaluation from the given file(s).
#                  Multiple files are concatenated then evaluated.
#                  If `-f` is not given, ~/.nemerlish_profile is loaded.
#
# Files:
#   ~/.nemerlish_profile    Auto-created on first run; opens namespace
#                            `Nemerle.Evaluation.Interpreter.Internals`
#                            and loads any user-supplied snippets.
#   ~/.nemerlish_history    Command history (readline-style).
#
# Interactive grammar:
#   Type Nemerle expressions terminated by `;;` to evaluate.
#   Type `Help;;` for the in-REPL help screen.
#   Type `Quit;;` to exit.
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ nemish                                # bare REPL
#   $ nemish -f a.n b.n                     # preload definitions
#   Welcome to Nemerle interpreter (using ncc 1.2.x.0).
#   Please enter expressions appended with ";;".
#   Type "Help;;" for more info.
#
#   > def fact (n : int) : int { if (n < 2) 1 else n * fact (n - 1) } ;;
#   def fact = ... : int -> int
#   > fact (10) ;;
#   3628800 : int
#
# Companion binary:
#   ncc — the Nemerle compiler.  The `ncc` binary is ALREADY in the
#   corpus under a DIFFERENT package (Vercel's @vercel/ncc Node.js
#   compiler).  Nemerle's `ncc` is the CIL-targeting Nemerle compiler
#   and uses Nemerle.Utility.Getopt for its rich option surface (see
#   ncc/main.n for the canonical example of the Getopt library).
#
# =============================================================================

_nemish() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -C \
        '-f[read code from file(s) for evaluation]:*:file:_files -g "*.n"' \
        '*:nemerle file:_files -g "*.n"' && ret=0

    return ret
}

_nemish "$@"
